━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
II.  SUBMISSION I — CHAIN-OF-CUSTODY ENTIRELY ABSENT: FSL REPORT INADMISSIBLE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The most fundamental infirmity in the prosecution's case is the complete absence
of any chain-of-custody documentation for the cement mortar samples. The
prosecution has not produced — and cannot produce — any record showing who
collected the samples, from which precise locations, at what time, in what
manner, how they were sealed, how they were transported, who received them at
the FSL, under what storage conditions they were kept, and who handled them at
each stage of testing. This is not a minor procedural lapse; it is a foundational
evidentiary failure that strikes at the very root of the prosecution's case.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Kattavellai @ Devakar v. State of Tamil Nadu,
Criminal Appeal No. 1672/2019, decided 15 July 2025 (2025 INSC 845), by a
three-judge bench of Justice Vikram Nath, Justice Sanjay Karol, and Justice
Sandeep Mehta, laid down binding nationwide guidelines:

    "Right from the point of collection to the logical end, i.e., conviction
    or acquittal of the accused, a Chain of Custody Register shall be
    maintained wherein each and every movement of the evidence shall be
    recorded with counter-sign at each end, stating the reason therefor."

The Court further directed that no package shall be opened, altered, or resealed
without express authorisation from the trial court. In the present case, not a
single link in the chain of custody has been documented.

This principle was reaffirmed by the Hon'ble Supreme Court in Surendra Koli v.
State of Uttar Pradesh (Curative Petition, decided 11 November 2025):

    "There was no credible chain of custody or expert testimony establishing
    the link between the accused and the physical evidence. Recoveries made
    without recording the statement of the accused by the police are not
    admissible as evidence under the Evidence law."

The seven chain-of-custody gaps in the present case:

┌────┬──────────────────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┐
│ #  │ Required Record                      │ Status in Present Case       │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
