├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
│ 3  │ Dispatch register / malkhana entry   │ ABSENT — not produced        │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
│ 4  │ FSL inward register + seal           │ ABSENT — not produced        │
│    │ verification letter                  │                              │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
│ 5  │ Storage conditions log at FSL        │ ABSENT — not produced        │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
│ 6  │ Analyst worksheet + machine logs     │ ABSENT — not produced        │
├────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
│ 7  │ Custody transfer log with timestamps │ ABSENT — not produced        │
└────┴──────────────────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────┘

The Uttarakhand High Court (LiveLaw, 28 March 2026) has held: "A conviction must
rest on legally proved evidence and not suspicion, however strong, and that in
the absence of a duly established chain of custody, forensic evidence loses its
evidentiary value and cannot be treated as conclusive." [SECONDARY — obtain
full citation before filing]

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
III.  SUBMISSION II — EX-PARTE SAMPLING VIOLATES MANDATORY PROTOCOLS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The samples were collected entirely ex-parte, without any notice to or presence
of the Petitioner or his authorised representative. This violates mandatory
requirements of the Bureau of Indian Standards and the CPWD, binding on all
public works investigations in India.

┌──────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────────────┬─────────────┐
│ Protocol             │ Mandatory Requirement                │ Compliance  │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────┤
│ IS 3535:1986 Cl. 4.1 │ Supplier/contractor representative   │ NOT COMPLIED│
│                      │ must be present at sampling          │             │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────┤
│ IS 3535:1986 Cl. 6.2 │ Minimum 5 representative locations   │ NOT COMPLIED│
│                      │ for statistical reliability          │             │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────┤
│ CPWD Manual 2023     │ Joint sampling by Engineer-in-Charge │ NOT COMPLIED│
│ §§3.7.4 & 12.2.1     │ and Contractor; joint sealing with   │             │
│                      │ signatures of both parties           │             │
├──────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────────────┼─────────────┤
│ BNSS 2023 §105       │ Panchnama in presence of independent │ NOT COMPLIED│
│                      │ witnesses at site of seizure         │             │
└──────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────────────┴─────────────┘

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Punjab v. Baldev Singh, (1999) 6 SCC 172:

    "Where a statute or official manual prescribes a specific procedure for
    the collection of evidence, strict compliance is not merely directory but
    mandatory, and departure therefrom creates a presumption of prejudice to
    the accused."

The right to be present at the collection of evidence is a facet of the
fundamental principle of natural justice — audi alteram partem. The contractor
was deprived of the ability to verify that samples were taken from representative
locations, that the correct methodology was followed, that samples were not
contaminated, and that sealing was done properly.


IV.  SUBMISSION III — NO RESERVE SAMPLE: ACCUSED DEPRIVED OF INDEPENDENT TESTING


This is a new and decisive ground, supported by a 2025 ruling of the Madras High
Court and the mandatory requirements of IS 3535:1986.

IS 3535:1986, Clause 5.7.5 — the BIS standard governing hydraulic cement
sampling — mandates a three-way division of every sample collected:

    "The laboratory sample and the composite sample shall be divided into
    three equal parts, one for the purchaser, another for the supplier, and
    the third to be used as a referee sample. The referee sample shall be
    used in case of a dispute between the purchaser and the supplier."

In a criminal investigation: prosecution = purchaser; accused contractor =
supplier. The prosecution was required to divide the mortar samples into three
equal parts and provide one part to the Petitioner for independent retesting.
The prosecution failed to do so. The Petitioner was permanently deprived of his
statutory right to a counter-sample.

The Hon'ble Madras High Court in C.J. Christopher Signi v. State of Tamil Nadu,
2025 SCC OnLine Mad 3214, decided 09 July 2025 (Justice B. Pugalendhi), held:

    "The accused is entitled to a fair opportunity to disprove the allegations
    against him. Denial of access to forensic comparison in the face of
    specific material forming part of defence evidence amounts to curtailment
    of such a right."

The Court further held:

    "The apprehension of possible tampering or alteration did not constitute
    valid justification for refusing forensic examination. On the contrary,
    such concerns strengthened the case for expert analysis. Any determination
    regarding whether the material was altered could only be made by a
    competent forensic authority, and not through assumptions or oral
    statements made by lay witnesses."

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Kattavellai (2025 INSC 845) further directed that
no sample package shall be opened, altered, or resealed without express
authorisation from the trial court. If the prosecution consumed the entire
sample without court authorisation, this is an independent violation of the
binding Supreme Court guidelines.

The consequences of this violation are severe:
(a) The Petitioner cannot independently verify the FSL findings.
(b) The prosecution cannot prove that the tested material was the same as that
    collected from the site — the burden under Damu (2000) 6 SCC 269 cannot
    be discharged.
(c) The Petitioner's right to a fair trial under Article 21 has been violated.
(d) Adverse inference must be drawn under Section 114 BSA 2023.


V.   SUBMISSION IV — WRONG STANDARD, RAIN CONTAMINATION, CARBONATED LAYER


The FSL report suffers from a foundational scientific error: the prosecution
applied IS 1199:2018 — "Methods of Sampling and Analysis of Fresh Concrete" —
to hardened masonry mortar in existing stone masonry. IS 1199:2018 explicitly
applies only to fresh concrete. It has no application whatsoever to hardened
cement mortar that has been in place for years in an existing masonry structure.


 Standard          Scope / Application                   Applicable?    

 IS 1199:2018      Fresh concrete only (Scope, Cl. 1)    WRONG —        
 [USED BY PROS.]   Not applicable to hardened mortar      Foundational   
                                                         Error          

 IS 2250:1981      Masonry mortars — preparation & use   CORRECT        
 [CORRECT STD.]    Only BIS standard for masonry mortar  Indian Std.    

 ASTM C1324        Forensic examination of hardened      CORRECT        
 [CORRECT INTL.]   masonry mortar; §§7-8: remove         Intl. Std.     
                   carbonated outer layer before                        
                   sampling                                             

 IS 13311 (1-2)    Non-Destructive Testing of existing   CORRECT NDT    
                   masonry structures (UPV/Rebound)      not used       

 IS 4031 (Pt. 6)   27+/-2 deg.C + controlled humidity    VIOLATED —     
                   mandatory for testing                  impossible in  
                                                         storm          

 ASTM C780 §6.1    "Samples must be protected from       VIOLATED —     
                   rain and moisture; otherwise sample   samples taken  
                   is invalid."                          during storm   


ASTM C1324, Sections 7 and 8, mandates that before sampling hardened mortar
joints, the carbonated outer layer — which in mortar joints over fifteen years
old can extend to a depth of 10 to 15 millimetres — must be removed, because
this carbonated layer has a compressive strength 30 to 50 per cent lower than
the original mortar. If samples are taken from the outer surface without removing
this layer, they will invariably "fail" strength tests — not because the original
construction was defective, but because of natural weathering over time.

The samples were collected on 28-12-2011 during heavy rainfall and storm.
ASTM C780 Section 6.1 states: "Samples must be protected from rain and moisture;
otherwise sample is invalid." BS EN 1015-2 Section 4.3.1 classifies weather
protection as a "Mandatory Precondition" for valid sampling. None of these
requirements could have been met during a storm.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu, (2000) 6 SCC 269:

    "Where the foundational facts upon which an expert opinion is based are
    themselves unreliable or contaminated, the expert opinion built thereon
    cannot be treated as conclusive evidence."

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Tomaso Bruno v. State of Uttar Pradesh,
(2015) 7 SCC 178:

    "Expert evidence is a weak type of evidence and the court is not bound
    to accept it. Where the expert evidence is based on assumptions or on a
    defective foundation, it cannot be relied upon."


VI.  SUBMISSION V — NO PANCHNAMA, NO SITE LOG, NO IMD RECORDS


The prosecution has not produced any contemporaneous records:


 #   Document Required                             Status                 

 1   Spot memo / panchnama at sampling site        ABSENT                 

 2   Site-inspection log (pre/post collapse)       ABSENT                 

 3   Photographs of extraction process             ABSENT                 

 4   IMD / local weather records for 28-12-2011    ABSENT                 

 5   Structural condition report (pre-collapse)    ABSENT                 

 6   Notice to contractor for sampling attendance  ABSENT                 

 7   IS 2250:1981 / ASTM C1324 compliance record   ABSENT                 


The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Maharashtra v. Damu, (2000) 6 SCC 269:

    "Where the prosecution relies heavily on the report of the forensic
    science laboratory, the foundational burden lies on the prosecution to
    prove beyond reasonable doubt that the samples sent to the laboratory
    were exactly the same as those seized from the spot. Without a panchnama
    prepared at the site in the presence of independent witnesses, this
    burden cannot be discharged."

Without a panchnama, the prosecution cannot establish the identity of the
samples. The FSL report rests on an entirely unverifiable foundation.


VII.  SUBMISSION VI — FORCE MAJEURE: THIS COURT'S OWN JUDICIAL NOTICE


The collapse occurred on 28-12-2011 during heavy rainfall and storm. The National
Building Code 2016/2023, Section 3.4, and the CPWD Manual Appendix C classify
extreme weather events as Force Majeure, exempting contractors from liability.

The Rajasthan High Court, Division Bench (Justice Sunil Beniwal + Justice Arun
Monga), in RSMML v. Contractor, decided 30 March 2026, held:

    "The contradictory approach of the State — acknowledging force majeure
    in its internal records while simultaneously terminating the contract on
    the same grounds — cannot be upheld. A contractor cannot be penalised
    for delays that the State's own note-sheets acknowledged as force majeure."

Most significantly, this Hon'ble Court itself, in its suo motu PIL proceedings
arising from the collapse of a government school building in Piplodi village,
Banswara district, Rajasthan (29 July 2025), by a bench of Justice Mahendra
Kumar Goyal and Justice Ashok Kumar Jain, directed the closure of 86,934
dilapidated classrooms across Rajasthan and observed:

    "Building safe schools should be priority for architects, engineers,
    policy makers, administrators and emergency response planners."

In the continuing proceedings through 2025 and 2026, this Hon'ble Court has
repeatedly taken judicial notice that structural collapses in Rajasthan are
caused by a combination of extreme weather events, pre-existing structural
deterioration, and maintenance failures — and has criticised the State for
failing to address these systemic causes.

If this Hon'ble Court has judicially noticed that thousands of public structures
in Rajasthan are unsafe due to age, maintenance failure, and extreme weather,
it cannot simultaneously permit a criminal prosecution of a contractor for a
collapse that occurred during a storm, on the basis of a forensic report vitiated
by the defects described above.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Jacob Mathew v. State of Punjab, (2005) 6 SCC 1,
Para 48:

    "Mere lack of necessary care, precaution and attention cannot be
    considered as rash or negligent act. Negligence means breach of a duty
    caused by omission to do something which a reasonable man would do."


VIII.  SUBMISSION VII — NO PRIMA FACIE CASE: DISCHARGE IS MANDATORY


The cumulative effect of the six defects above is that the prosecution's case
rests entirely on a single FSL report that is inadmissible, unreliable, and
scientifically unsound. There is no independent evidence of corruption, bribery,
or criminal intent. There is no evidence that the Petitioner was responsible for
the collapse as opposed to the extreme weather conditions.

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in Union of India v. Prafulla Kumar Samal,
(1979) 3 SCC 4, Para 10:

    "If the material placed on record discloses nothing more than a
    suspicion, the accused is entitled to be discharged."

The Hon'ble Supreme Court in State of Bihar v. Ramesh Singh, (1977) 4 SCC 39,
Para 5:

    "At the stage of framing of charge, the Court has to see whether the
    material produced makes out a prima facie case. If the material discloses
    nothing more than suspicion, discharge is mandatory."

The prosecution's material — even taken at its highest — discloses nothing more
than suspicion. The Petitioner is therefore entitled to be discharged under
Section 250 of the Bharatiya Nagarik Suraksha Sanhita, 2023.


IX.  PRAYER


In view of the foregoing, it is most respectfully prayed that this Hon'ble Court
may be pleased to:

(i)   Quash and set aside the criminal proceedings in Special Session Case No.
      1/2025 pending before the learned Special Session Judge (PCA), Udaipur,
      arising from FIR No. 496/2011, as the same are an abuse of the process of
      law and no prima facie case is made out against the Petitioner;

(ii)  Alternatively, direct the learned trial court to discharge the Petitioner
      under Section 250 BNSS 2023 (erstwhile Section 227 Cr.P.C.) on the grounds
      set out hereinabove;

(iii) Direct the prosecution to disclose whether the mortar samples were divided
      into three equal parts as mandated by IS 3535:1986 Clause 5.7.5, and if
      not, draw adverse inference under Section 114 of the Bharatiya Sakshya
      Adhiniyam, 2023;

(iv)  Direct the prosecution to produce all original records of sample collection,
      sealing, transport, FSL receipt, and testing, failing which adverse inference
      be drawn under Section 114 BSA 2023;

(v)   Declare the FSL mortar report inadmissible as evidence on account of the
      procedural and scientific defects enumerated herein;

(vi)  Alternatively, permit the Petitioner to conduct independent retesting of
      the reserve sample (if any) at a NABL-accredited laboratory of his choice,
      under the supervision of a court-appointed observer; and

(vii) Pass such other and further orders as this Hon'ble Court may deem fit and
      proper in the facts and circumstances of the case.


